{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649202","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649202"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:33+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:02:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18353"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18353","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18353"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.2,0.3,0.05,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11071"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74341"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11071","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11071"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18353"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"59832"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"11270"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74341"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following provides active support to the arches of the foot?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plantar aponeurosis","Long plantar ligament","Plantar calcaneonavicular ligament","Short plantar ligament","Tibialis posterior tendon"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eplantar aponeurosis\u003C/strong\u003E is a thick band of connective tissue that runs along the sole of the foot. It plays a crucial role in providing active support to the arches of the foot by maintaining tension during weight-bearing activities, such as standing and walking. This tension helps to absorb shock and maintain the structural integrity of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elong plantar ligament\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eplantar calcaneonavicular ligament\u003C/strong\u003E, and \u003Cstrong\u003Eshort plantar ligament\u003C/strong\u003E are all ligaments that provide passive support to the arches of the foot. They help maintain the foot\u0027s structure but do not actively adjust tension during movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibialis posterior tendon\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in supporting the medial arch of the foot, but it is not the primary structure providing active support. It works in conjunction with other structures to maintain arch stability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The plantar aponeurosis provides active support to the arches of the foot by maintaining tension during weight-bearing activities.","Ligaments such as the long plantar ligament, plantar calcaneonavicular ligament, and short plantar ligament provide passive support to the foot arches."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [I